{
  "text": "An increase in the apparent permeability of the brush border observed at sublethal levels of saponins may have important implications for the uptake of macromolecules, such as allergens, whose passage through the epithelium is normally somewhat restricted [CITATION_1] . The presence of Gypsophila saponins enhanced the uptake of b lactoglobulin, a milk allergen in the jejunal loops' tips of brown Norway rats [CITATION_2] . Histological investigation of the mucosal epithelium exposed to saponin revealed damage, especially of the villi. Rats fed the unwashed bitter quinoa diets (containing saponins that caused rapid depolarisation of the small-intestinal mucosa, even at concentrations of less than 50 mg/ml) demonstrated growth impairment and decreased food conversion efficiency [CITATION_3] . Avenacosides that were haemolytic in the crude extract significantly increased the passage of ovalbumin in rat intestine in vitro at a concentration of 1 mg/ml but did not affect the active transport of glucose [CITATION_4] . However, when given in vivo in the same experiment the saponins did not affect the transport of bovine serum albumin across the intestine wall. Quillaja saponins were able to increase uptake of human G globulin into the body, when fed to tilapia or administered by anal incubation [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Rat intestines have been shown to offset the damage to small-intestinal mucosal cells caused by dietary saponins (up to 1\u00b75 %) by continuous proliferation .",
